>>d1d8166b-12b0-4efd-8dcb-aed872d78b31
I was referring to "CPU design tech" at a slightly higher abstraction level than that.
What I mean is more optimized caches, changing the way the instruction is implemented, more advanced hardware-level pipelining and other such things that can improve the processor at the same level of lithography.
Look through books like these, https://wiki.osdev.org/Books#Computer_Architecture and you will see what I mean.
An example of what I mean by "keeping up with the latest in CPU design tech" is going through academic papers like http://www.ece.lsu.edu/tca/papers/fields04interaction.pdf and implementing whatever seems useful. If something doesn't work, it doesn't matter. Your CPU would pretty much be a prototyping board anyway, you can easily revert changes if they don't make it better.

>>7c8a5b30-d6d8-4ff0-8e10-003a0a18d6a2
>Level 1
>Level 2
Speaking of which, we need to hurry up and create a level 3; it would have to be something like a decentralized anonymity network that doesnt depend on having millions of users to remain anonymous.

Have it based off things like the pluggable transports Tor uses to hide from Egyptian ISPs, but put almost all the development effort into invisibility. It must be so well-designed that even with the source code, nobody can even detect the traffic.

I'm not too far along with my research, but from a preliminary investigation, it will be very possible (and comparatively easy compared to unrestricted traffic) to remain anonymous if we limit the traffic to a single, JSON/XML/whatever-based text protocol for text-based messages. This will relax the high bandwidth and low latency needed, as some of Tor's main threats to its users' anonymity are, as outlined in its design documents, due to the compromises and anonymity trade-offs they had to make to get their high bandwidth and low latency.

>A global passive adversary is the most commonly assumed threat when analyzing theoretical anonymity designs. But like all practical low-latency systems, Tor does not protect against such a strong adversary.
This is actually what it says in the Tor design document. Our technology has advanced so much in the 15 years since that document (which smells of our luminescent-skinned associates BTW) that we ought to be able to make something better.

We need to roll our own crypto (in spirit). What I mean by this is, like Theo de Raadt, I think that "security-related research and development should only be done by massive corporations with billions of dollars under massive peer review" is shit. This has already been disproved in at least one case, like that one time El Chapo's IT guy rolled his own crypto for a worldwide encrypted VOIP network. The FBI had no idea at all how to break it for multiple years, so they ended up just paying off the IT guy.

How that translates to our case, is that it is possible for /tech/nicians to really make some good shit. We are 130+ IQ white men who spend all our time on our computers, we can at least win against Pajeet and the rest of the diversity hires at the NSA (Ghidra was written in motherfucking Java, you can't tell me that the NSA isn't full of fuckwits).

TL;DR we need anonymity that doesn't depend on Tor, as it is, by design, not good enough for people wanting to thwart even blanket surveillance.

posts.subject: WWYD
posts.body:
You man the counter at your local milsurp/hunting/outdoors shop, and it's just a normal day.
You didn't bring your survival kit or bug out bag, it's not like anything's going to happen anyway right?
Suddenly, big boom. Screams. You see a mushroom cloud in the distance. It's far enough to not melt your skin, but too close to be out of the radiation zone. You're already too late to escape the initial exposure of radiation, now you have to worry about the radioactive gas clouds and general SHTF unrest.
You have 1 minute to grab all you need and book it to the nearest nuclear shelter or other such bunker.
WWYD
